We want to make sure all the application routes are documented in swagger. 

We can automatically retrieve all of the express routes with the following code:

```TypeScript
  const routes: any[] = [];
  app._router.stack.forEach(function (middleware: any) {
    if (middleware.route) {
      // routes registered directly on the app
      routes.push(middleware.route);
    } else if (middleware.name === 'router') {
      // router middleware
      middleware.handle.stack.forEach(function (handler: any) {
        const route = handler.route;
        route && routes.push(route);
      });
    }
  });
```

The printed output looks like this.
```
[                                                                                                                                                                                                                  
  Route { path: '/', stack: [ [Layer] ], methods: { get: true } },                                                                                                                                                 
  Route { path: '/nonce', stack: [ [Layer] ], methods: { post: true } },                                                                                                                                           
...                          
```

# Definition of Done

- Create a function that retrieves all of the routes from an express application
- Filter any routes that are not related to the application (for example the swagger route itself does not need to be documented)
- Create unit tests that use these functions to check if our swagger files are documenting all of the routes. These tests enforce the documentation such that no extra code will be needed at runtime.

